					m_sNote = "Think of Entry/Exit as a \'core loop\', in the center of the graph. Only the \'Tag says no\' state can break us out of it.\n\nNote that when transitioning to the \'Tag says no\' state, we are using trickery to decide whether to play the Exit animation based on whether b_sprint was true just now (that is to say: were we sprinting\?). Pay close attention to how \'Start Cycle At\' is used towards the \'Tag says no\' state! If we are currently in Entry, we are sprinting, therefore going to \'Tag says no\' must play an exit, so we transition \'normally\'. If we are currently in Exit, that means we have stopped sprinting a while ago, OR, and this is the fun part, we might be stopping sprinting right now... therefore make \'Tag says no\' play the exit transition animation with the *same cycle* as the Exit state. If we did indeed stop sprinting a while ago, the Exit animation finished a while ago too, meaning it\'s got a cycle value of 1.0, and because that gets passed, that animation won\'t play twice!\n\nThis lets me greatly simplify the amount of states involved. \n\nInit as if entry/exit may seem like a pointless layer at first, but they\'re needed in case b_deploy_skip is used. The 0.02 time conditions are needed because Animgraph needs 1 tick to properly set the cycle value to 1 when coming out of this initialization step (we want to enter the core loop of conditions, but without actually playing, hence needing to set the cycle value)\n\n"
					m_states = 
